==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Obstetrical
<hw>Ob*stet"ric*al</hw> <pr>(⟦ocr⟧b*st⟦ecr⟧t"r⟦icr⟧*k⟦ait⟧l)</pr>,
}</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>obstetricius</ets>, fr.
<ets>obstetrix</ets>, <ets>-icis</ets>, a midwife, fr.
<ets>obstare</ets> to stand before: cf. F.
<ets>obst⟦eacute⟧trique</ets>. See <er>Obstacle</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Of or pertaining to childbirth, midwifery, or the period around the
time of the birth of children; <as>as, the <ex>obstetric</ex>
art</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to obstetrics; <as>as, the
<ex>obstetric</ex> unit of a hospital</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Obstetrical toad</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a
European toad of the genus <gen>Alytes</gen>, especially <spn>Alytes
obstetricans</spn>. The eggs are laid in a string which the male winds
around his legs, and carries about until the young are
hatched.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 993 --></p>

<p><ent>Obstetricate</ent>⟦br⟧
